    Apache Flume - open-source tool designed to collect, aggregate, and move large amounts of log data (or event data)
                   from various sources into centralized storage systems
    In short: Apache Flume is basically a data pipeline tool specialized for moving log/event data efficiently into big data systems

    Flows like:    Source → Channel → Sink

    Used in big data environments to:
	    •	collect logs from servers, apps, or devices
	    •	stream data into systems like Apache Hadoop (especially HDFS)
	    •	handle high-throughput, real-time data ingestion

    Flume is built around a pipeline with three main components:
	    •	Source – where the data comes from (e.g., log files, web servers)
	    •	Channel – temporary storage (memory or disk buffer)
	    •	Sink – where the data goes (e.g., Hadoop, databases)

    Key features
	    •	Scalable: can handle huge volumes of data
	    •	Reliable: ensures data delivery even if failures happen
	    •	Flexible: supports many data sources and destinations
	    •   Fault tolerant
	    •   Centralized data storage
	    •   Data ingestion
	    •   Large Data Set
	    •	Streaming: works in near real-time

    A common setup:
	    •	Web servers generate logs
	    •	Flume collects those logs
	    •	Sends them into Hadoop for analysis



